{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_4epe5vc9l6nm_1","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Sefer Yetzirah | Sefaria Library\nURL: https://www.sefaria.org/Sefer_Yetzirah?tab=contents\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nSefer Yetzirah | Sefaria Library\n\nSefer Yetzirah\n\nContents\n\nVersions\n\nChapter\n\nSefer Yetzirah | Sefaria Library\nSkip to main content\nSearch\nSign Up\n\n\nSite Language\nEnglishЧўЧ‘ЧЁЧҷЧӘ\n\nSefaria\n\nLibrary\n\n\nVoices\n\n\nDevelopers\n\nMore from Sefaria вҖә\n\nLog inSign up\nSite Language\nEnglishЧўЧ‘ЧЁЧҷЧӘ\nNew AdditionsHelp\nSefer Yetzirah\nHebrew Language Toggle IconEnglish Language Toggle Icon\nKabbalah\nStart Reading\nContents\nVersions\nChapter\n123456\n# About This Text\nComposed: c.200 BCE вҖ“ c.200 CE\nSefer Yetzirah (the \"Book of Creation\") is the title of the earliest extant book of Jewish esotericism. This short, enigmatic book describes how God created the universe through вҖң32 secret paths of wisdom,вҖқ composed of the 22 letters of the Hebrew alphabet plus the ten вҖңsefirot,вҖқ which in this early period refer simply to вҖңnumbersвҖқ even as they allude to metaphysical principles. The origin of the text is unknown and debated. Based on the language of the text, scholars date it to between the third and sixth centuries, admitting some later additions. Some attribute its origin to Abraham the patriarch and others to the tanna R. Akiva, who, according to the Babylonian Talmud, engaged in mystical activities. Given the subject matter and the workвҖҷs laconic style, it has been the subject of many varied commentaries.\n# Related Topics\nKabbalah\nSefirot (Kabbalah)\nZohar\nGolems\nTeli\nMore\n# Download Text\nSelect VersionOpen dropdown\nSelect FormatOpen dropdown\nDownload\n#\nAboutHelpContact UsNewsletterBlogInstagramFacebookYouTubeShopTermsPrivacy PolicyWays to GiveDonate\n\n---\n\nTitle: Sefer Yetzirah, the Cube of Space, and the Emergence of the Tree of Life\nURL: http://www.maqom.com/journal/paper33.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: Christopher P Benton\nHighlights:\nSefer Yetzirah\n[...]\nIn this paper we will explore select passages from the Sefer Yetzirah in order to see how the twenty-two letters of the Hebrew alphabet were used to define a cube as an early model of the universe, and we will trace the development of the ten sefirot from the Sefer Yetzirah through the later texts of the Bahir and the Zohar. Along the way we will also find clues regarding how this early model for creation, that some call the Cube of Space, transformed itself into the now ubiquitous model of the Tree of Life. And finally, we will show how the modern day Tree of Life, developed by Rabbi Isaac Luria in sixteenth century Safed, brilliantly reconciles the Kabbalah of the Sefer Yetzirah with that of the more recent Zohar. We begin, though, with a line-by-line analysis of various passages of the Sefer Yetzirah.\n[...]\nвҖңWith 32 mystical paths (netivot peliyot) of wisdom engraved Yah, the Lord of Hosts, the God of Israel, the Living God, King of the universe, El Shaddai, merciful and gracious, high and exalted, dwelling in eternity, whose name is holy. He is lofty and holy, and He created His universe with three books, with text (sefer), with number (safar), and with communication (sippur).вҖқ (Sefer Yetzirah 1:1)\n[...]\nreference, is the tree with both Hebrew and English names given for the sefirot. Also, we see that in this final diagram the sefirot have achieved an existence independent of the letters while at the same time, we have the sefirot and the letters melded together into a single schematic for representing the вҖңthirty-two mystical paths of wisdomвҖқ that are mentioned at the start of the Sefer Yetzirah. Furthermore, modern interpretations of the Tree of Life suggest that the right side of the tree be interpreted in terms of intuitive, holistic right brain functions, the left side in terms of the more analytical, structure oriented left hemisphere of the brain, the bottom of the tree in terms of concrete physical reality, and the top of the tree in terms of that which is more abstract and non-physical.\n[...]\nThe next obvious thing about the structure of the Tree of Life is that there are seven vertical paths, and as might be expected, these paths correspond to the seven double letters, bet-gimmel-dalet-kaf-peh-resh-tav, discussed in the Sefer Yetzirah. Notice, however, how they are placed on the tree. We have bet on the upper right side, gimmel on the upper left, and dalet in between. This right-left-center pattern replicates the pattern found in the Sefer Yetzirah of one thing opposite another with a mediating principle in between. And as we go down the tree we see this same right-left-center pattern repeated again with kaf-peh-resh, and then we end with tav at the bottom.\n\n---\n\nTitle: YEбә’IRAH, SEFER - JewishEncyclopedia.com\nURL: https://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/13386-sefer-yezirah\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nits turn, by the prototypes of the three primordial substances when they became realities. Simultaneously with the prototypes, or at least before the real world, space was produced, and it is here conceived as the three dimensions with their opposite directions. The spirit of God, the three primordial elements, and the six dimensions of space form the \"ten Sefirot,\" which, like the spirit of God, exist only ideally, being \"ten Sefirot without reality\" as the text designates them. Their name is possibly derived from the fact that as numbers express only the relations of two objects to each other, so the ten Sefirot are only abstractions and not realities. Again, as the numbers from two to ten are derived from the number one, so the ten Sefirot are derived from one, the spirit of God. The spirit of God, however, is not only the commencement but also the conclusion of the Sefirot, \"their end being in their beginning and their beginning in their end, even as the flame is connected with the coal\"(i. 7). Hence the Sefirot must not be conceived as emanations in the ordinary sense of the word, but rather as modifications of the spirit of God, which first changes to, then becomes water, and finally fire, the last being no further removed from God than the first. Besides these abstract ten Sefirot, which are conceived only ideally, the twenty-two letters of the alphabet produced the material world, for they are real, and are the formative powers of all existence and development. By means of these elements the actual creation of the world took place, and the ten Sefirot, which before this had only an ideal existence, became realities. This is, then, a modified form of the Talmudic doctrine that God created heaven and earth by means of letters (Ber. 58a). The explanation on this point is very obscure, however, since the relation of the twenty-two letters to the ten Sefirot is not clearly defined. The first sentence of the book reads: \"Thirty-two paths, marvels of wisdom, hath God engraved . . . ,\" these paths being then explained as the ten Sefirot and the twenty-two letters. While the Sefirot are expressly designated as \"abstracts\" (), it is said of the letters: \"Twenty-two letters: He drew them, hewed them, combined them, weighed them, interchanged them, and through them produced the whole creation and everything that is destined to come into being\" (ii. 2). The basal theory of the letters apparently regards them neither as independent substances nor yet as mere forms, so that they are, as it were, the connecting-link between essence and form. They are designated, therefore, as the instruments by which the real world, which consists of essence and form, was produced from the Sefirot, which are merely formless essences.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Sefer Yetzirah\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sefer_Yezirah\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nBy thirty-two mysterious paths of wisdom Yah has engraved [all things], [who is] the Lord of hosts, the God of Israel, the living God, the Almighty God, He that is uplifted and exalted, He that Dwells forever, and whose Name is holy; having created His world by three [derivatives] of [the Hebrew root-word] sefar : namely, sefer (a book), sefor (a count) and sippur (a story), along with ten calibrations of empty space and twenty-two letters [of the Hebrew alphabet], [of which] three are principal [letters] (i.e. Чҗ Чһ Ч©вҖҺ), seven are double-sounding [consonants] (i.e. Ч‘Ч’\"Ч“ ЧӣЧӨЧЁ\"ЧӘвҖҺ) and twelve are ordinary [letters] (i.e. Ч” Ч• Ч– Ч— Чҳ Чҷ Чң Ч  ЧЎ Чў ЧҰ Ч§вҖҺ).\n[...]\nThe Sefer Yetzirah describes how the universe was created by the \"God of Israel\" (a list of all of God's Hebrew names appears in the first sentence of the book) through \"32 wondrous ways of wisdom\":\n[...]\nThe book describes the method for using the ten sefirot and the 22 Hebrew letters to gain Divine Insight/Secret using Abraham's tongue. God's covenant with Abraham is described as being twofold.\n[...]\nBesides these three\n[...]\n,\" a distinction\n[...]\nhave two different\n[...]\n, and the\n[...]\nwhich represent only one\n[...]\npossibly derived from\n[...]\nderived from one\n[...]\nsense of the\n[...]\n, but rather as modifications of\n[...]\n, then becomes\n[...]\nSefer Yet\n[...]\nBesides these abstract ten sefirot\n[...]\nare conceived only\n[...]\n, the twenty-two letters of the alphabet produced\n[...]\nmaterial world, for they are real, and are\n[...]\nformative powers of all existence and development. By means of these elements the actual creation of\n[...]\ntook place, and the ten sefirot\n[...]\nwhich before this had only an ideal existence, became realities. This is, then, a modified form of the Talmudic doctrine that God created heaven and earth by means of letters (Berakhot 58a). The explanation on this point is obscure since the relation of the twenty-two letters to the ten sefirot is not clearly defined.\n[...]\nThe first sentence of the book reads: \"Thirty-two paths, marvels of wisdom, hath God engraved...,\" these paths being then explained as the ten sefirot and the twenty-two letters. While the sefirot are expressly designated as \"abstracts\", it is said of the letters: \"Twenty-two letters: God drew them, hewed them, combined them, weighed them, interchanged them, and through them produced the whole creation and everything that is destined to come into being\" (ii. 2).\n[...]\nIn 2002, American mathematician Robert P. C. de Marrais named the pathions, or the 3\n[...]\n-dimensional hypercomplex numbers, after the 32 paths of wisdom in the Sefer Yetzirah.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Sefer Yetzirah and the 32 Paths of Creation | Mayim Achronim\nURL: https://www.mayimachronim.com/sefer-yetzirah-and-the-32-paths-of-creation/\nPublished: 2015-10-08T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: Efraim Palvanov\nHighlights:\nAlong with the 22 letters were the Ten Sefirot, divine energies that imbue everything within Creation. These Sefirot are sometimes said to parallel the 10 base numerical digits, from 0 to 9 (the word sefirah also means вҖңcountingвҖқ). Just as modern physicists might argue that the entire universe can be reduced to mathematical equations, Sefer Yetzirah reduces all of Creation down to these foundational numbers and letters. And so, Sefer Yetzirah begins by stating that God created the universe through lamed-beit netivot, thirty-two paths.\n[...]\nWhere exactly are the 32 Paths of Creation derived from? A careful analysis of the Genesis text shows that God (Elohim) is mentioned 32 times in the account of creation. Each of these 32 parallels the 32 paths. There are ten cases where the Torah says vayomer Elohim, вҖңAnd God saidвҖҰвҖқ in the first chapter. These 10 correspond to the Ten Sefirot. The remaining 22 mentions of God correspond to the 22 letters in the following way:\n[...]\nSefer Yetzirah breaks down the Hebrew alphabet into three groups: the вҖңmothersвҖқ (imaвҖҷot), the вҖңdoublesвҖқ (kefulot), and the вҖңelementalsвҖқ (peshutot). There are three mother letters: Aleph (Чҗ), Mem (Чһ), and Shin (Ч©). These are the вҖңmothersвҖқ because each is associated with one of the three primordial elements of Creation: Aleph is the root of air (avir, ЧҗЧ•ЧҷЧЁ), Mem is the root of water (mayim, ЧһЧҷЧқ), and Shin is the root of fire (esh, ЧҗЧ©). These three correspond to the three times that the Torah says вҖңGod madeвҖқ (Genesis 1:7, 16, and 25).\n[...]\nThe вҖңTree of LifeвҖқ depicting the Ten Sefirot, intertwined by the 22 Letters of the Hebrew Alphabet. Together, they make up the 32 Paths of Wisdom.\n[...]\nFinally, all of these are embedded in the most famous of Kabbalistic diagrams, the Etz Chaim, вҖңTree of LifeвҖқ. The 10 circles on the diagram correspond to the Ten Sefirot. The Sefirot are interconnected by 22 lines, corresponding to the 22 letters. There are three horizontal lines, corresponding to the three mother letters; seven vertical lines, corresponding to the seven doubled letters; and twelve diagonal lines, corresponding to the twelve elemental letters. This simple diagram amazingly captures a great deal of information, and is a key tool in KabbalahвҖ”as well as the first step towards creating your very own calf!\n\n---\n\nTitle: Text of \"Sefer Yetzirah\" Chapter 1\nURL: https://www.emol.org/kabbalah/seferyetzirah/text/index.html\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nWith 32 wonderous ways of wisdom, YAH, the Lord of Hosts, the Gd of Israel, the Living GD (El SHADAI), Omnipotent GD, extolled, Dweller up above whose habitation is eternity. His Name high and holy engraved His name, covenanted, drilled, and created his universe in 32 mysterious paths of wisdom through 3 Sepharim;\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Tree of Life вҖ” Interactive Map of the 10 Sephirot & 22 Paths | Cosmos Daily\nURL: https://cosmosdaily.co/tree-of-life\nPublished: 2026-05-10T08:22:46.000Z\nAuthor: Cosmos Daily\nHighlights:\nThe Tree of Life is the central diagram of Kabbalistic mysticism. Ten sephirot вҖ” emanations of the divine вҖ” are arranged in a specific geometric pattern, connected by twenty-two paths. Together they map the entire architecture of consciousness: from pure undifferentiated being at the top (Kether, the Crown) down through every stage of manifestation to the physical world at the bottom (Malkuth, the Kingdom).\n[...]\nThe tradition originates in medieval Jewish mysticism, was systematized by Isaac Luria in 16th-century Safed\n[...]\nand reached its modern form in the Hermetic Qabalah of the late-19th-century Golden Dawn вҖ” where it was integrated with Tarot, Western astrology, and ceremonial magic into the unified system that Cosmos Daily uses.\n[...]\nEvery sephirah\n[...]\n, virtue, and vice. Every path\n[...]\na Hebrew letter and a Tarot card. To\n[...]\nback to cosmos.\n[...]\nThe 22 paths connect the sephirot. Each carries a letter of the Hebrew alphabet and a Tarot Major Arcana вҖ” and twelve of them are also assigned to the twelve zodiac signs. When your Sun, Moon, and Ascendant fall on these paths, they become illuminated in your chart.\n[...]\nThe Tree of Life has two parallel histories: a Jewish Kabbalistic tradition that runs from the Sefer Yetzirah (3rdвҖ“6th century) through the Zohar (13th century) to the Lurianic synthesis of 16th-century Safed; and a Hermetic Qabalistic tradition that emerged in the late 19th century when the Golden Dawn вҖ” Mathers, Westcott, Regardie, Crowley, Dion Fortune вҖ” wove the Tree together with Tarot, Western astrology, and Hermetic alchemy into the unified esoteric framework that Cosmos Daily inherits.\n[...]\nThe Tree of Life is the central diagram of Kabbalistic mysticism вҖ” 10 sephirot connected by 22 paths, mapping the architecture of consciousness from pure being (Kether) down to the manifest world (Malkuth). It originates in medieval Jewish mysticism and was systematized in Western esotericism by the late-19th-century Golden Dawn.\n[...]\nThe 22 paths connect the 10 sephirot. Each path corresponds to one of the 22 letters of the Hebrew alphabet and one of the 22 Tarot Major Arcana. In Hermetic Qabalah, twelve of these paths are also assigned to the twelve zodiac signs вҖ” meaning your Sun, Moon, and Ascendant each illuminate a specific path on the Tree.\n[...]\nJewish Kabbalah is the original mystical tradition of Judaism, rooted in texts like the Zohar (13th century) and the work of Isaac Luria (16th century). Hermetic Qabalah (note the \"Q\" spelling) is the Western esoteric adaptation developed by the Golden Dawn вҖ” it integrates Tarot, Western astrology, alchemy, and ceremonial magic with the Tree of Life. Cosmos Daily uses the Hermetic Qabalah framework.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Sefirot\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sefirot\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nalshelut\n[...]\nЧЎЦөЧ“Ц¶ЧЁ Ч”ЦҙЧ©Ц°ЧҒЧӘЦ·ЦјЧңЦ°Ч©Ц°\n[...]\ndescending sequence of\n[...]\nAlternative configurations of the sefirot are interpreted by various schools in the historical evolution of Kabbalah, with each articulating differing spiritual aspects. The tradition of enumerating 10 is stated in the Sefer Yetzirah: \"Ten sefirot of nothingness, ten and not nine, ten and not eleven\". As altogether eleven sefirot are listed across the various schemes, two (Keter and Da'at) are seen as unconscious and conscious manifestations of the same principle, conserving the 10 categories. The sefirot are described as channels of divine creative life force or consciousness through which the unknowable divine essence is revealed to humankind.\n[...]\nThe original reference to the sefirot is found in the ancient Sefer Yetzirah\"The Book of Formation,\" attributed to the first Jewish patriarch, Abraham. However, the names of the sefirot as given in later Kabbalah are not specified there, but rather are only identified by their attributes \"forward,\" \"backward,\" \"right,\" \"left,\" \"down,\" \"up,\" \"light,\" \"darkness,\" \"good\" and \"evil.\" Further references to the sefirot, now with their later-accepted names, are elaborated on in the medieval Kabbalistic text of the Zohar, which is one of the core texts of Kabbalah.\n[...]\n16th-century rational synthesis of\n[...]\nbalah, the\n[...]\n4 Chesed - \"\n[...]\n\" 5 Gevurah - \"Discipline\" 6 Tiferet - \"Glory\" (Secondary emotions:) 7 Netzach - \"Victory\" 8 Hod - \"Splendour\" 9 Yesod - \"Foundation\" (Vessel to bring action:) 10 Malkuth - \"Kingdom\" Kingship\n[...]\nThese ten levels are associated with Kabbalah's four different \"Worlds\" or planes of existence, the main part from the perspective of the descending \"chain of progression\" (Seder hishtalshelut), that links the infinite divine Ein Sof with the finite, physical realm. In all Worlds, the 10 sefirot radiate, and are the divine channels through which every level is continuously created from nothing. Since they are the attributes through which the unknowable, infinite divine essence becomes revealed to the creations, all ten emanate in each World. Nonetheless, the structure of the Four Worlds arises because in each one, certain sefirot predominate. Each World is spiritual, apart from the lower aspect of the final World, which is the Asiyah Gashmi (\"Physical Asiyah\"), the physical Universe. Each World is progressively grosser and further removed from consciousness of the Divine, until in this World it is possible to be unaware of or to deny God. In descending order:\n[...]\n3. World of Formation (Hebrew: ЧҷЦ°ЧҰЦҙЧҷЧЁЦёЧ”, Yetzirah): On this level, creation is related to form. The Divine emotional sefirot of Chesed to Yesod predominate."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"79e3223a-ba20-4f6e-b874-a03376aa416a","uuid":"46dac830-cc8b-4e97-b444-b242bb2451c3","timestamp":"2026-06-10T17:41:25.103Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Sefer Yetzirah | Sefaria Library\nURL: https://www.sefaria.org/Sefer_Yetzirah?tab=contents\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nSefer Yetzirah | Sefaria Library\n\nSefer Yetzirah\n\nContents\n\nVersions\n\nChapter\n\nSefer Yetzirah | Sefaria Library\nSkip to main content\nSearch\nSign Up\n\n\nSite Language\nEnglishЧўЧ‘ЧЁЧҷЧӘ\n\nSefaria\n\nLibrary\n\n\nVoices\n\n\nDevelopers\n\nMore from Sefaria вҖә\n\nLog inSign up\nSite Language\nEnglishЧўЧ‘ЧЁЧҷЧӘ\nNew AdditionsHelp\nSefer Yetzirah\nHebrew Language Toggle IconEnglish Language Toggle Icon\nKabbalah\nStart Reading\nContents\nVersions\nChapter\n123456\n# About This Text\nComposed: c.200 BCE вҖ“ c.200 CE\nSefer Yetzirah (the \"Book of Creation\") is the title of the earliest extant book of Jewish esotericism. This short, enigmatic book describes how God created the universe through вҖң32 secret paths of wisdom,вҖқ composed of the 22 letters of the Hebrew alphabet plus the ten вҖңsefirot,вҖқ which in this early period refer simply to вҖңnumbersвҖқ even as they allude to metaphysical principles. The origin of the text is unknown and debated. Based on the language of the text, scholars date it to between the third and sixth centuries, admitting some later additions. Some attribute its origin to Abraham the patriarch and others to the tanna R. Akiva, who, according to the Babylonian Talmud, engaged in mystical activities. Given the subject matter and the workвҖҷs laconic style, it has been the subject of many varied commentaries.\n# Related Topics\nKabbalah\nSefirot (Kabbalah)\nZohar\nGolems\nTeli\nMore\n# Download Text\nSelect VersionOpen dropdown\nSelect FormatOpen dropdown\nDownload\n#\nAboutHelpContact UsNewsletterBlogInstagramFacebookYouTubeShopTermsPrivacy PolicyWays to GiveDonate\n\n---\n\nTitle: Sefer Yetzirah, the Cube of Space, and the Emergence of the Tree of Life\nURL: http://www.maqom.com/journal/paper33.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: Christopher P Benton\nHighlights:\nSefer Yetzirah\n[...]\nIn this paper we will explore select passages from the Sefer Yetzirah in order to see how the twenty-two letters of the Hebrew alphabet were used to define a cube as an early model of the universe, and we will trace the development of the ten sefirot from the Sefer Yetzirah through the later texts of the Bahir and the Zohar. Along the way we will also find clues regarding how this early model for creation, that some call the Cube of Space, transformed itself into the now ubiquitous model of the Tree of Life. And finally, we will show how the modern day Tree of Life, developed by Rabbi Isaac Luria in sixteenth century Safed, brilliantly reconciles the Kabbalah of the Sefer Yetzirah with that of the more recent Zohar. We begin, though, with a line-by-line analysis of various passages of the Sefer Yetzirah.\n[...]\nвҖңWith 32 mystical paths (netivot peliyot) of wisdom engraved Yah, the Lord of Hosts, the God of Israel, the Living God, King of the universe, El Shaddai, merciful and gracious, high and exalted, dwelling in eternity, whose name is holy. He is lofty and holy, and He created His universe with three books, with text (sefer), with number (safar), and with communication (sippur).вҖқ (Sefer Yetzirah 1:1)\n[...]\nreference, is the tree with both Hebrew and English names given for the sefirot. Also, we see that in this final diagram the sefirot have achieved an existence independent of the letters while at the same time, we have the sefirot and the letters melded together into a single schematic for representing the вҖңthirty-two mystical paths of wisdomвҖқ that are mentioned at the start of the Sefer Yetzirah. Furthermore, modern interpretations of the Tree of Life suggest that the right side of the tree be interpreted in terms of intuitive, holistic right brain functions, the left side in terms of the more analytical, structure oriented left hemisphere of the brain, the bottom of the tree in terms of concrete physical reality, and the top of the tree in terms of that which is more abstract and non-physical.\n[...]\nThe next obvious thing about the structure of the Tree of Life is that there are seven vertical paths, and as might be expected, these paths correspond to the seven double letters, bet-gimmel-dalet-kaf-peh-resh-tav, discussed in the Sefer Yetzirah. Notice, however, how they are placed on the tree. We have bet on the upper right side, gimmel on the upper left, and dalet in between. This right-left-center pattern replicates the pattern found in the Sefer Yetzirah of one thing opposite another with a mediating principle in between. And as we go down the tree we see this same right-left-center pattern repeated again with kaf-peh-resh, and then we end with tav at the bottom.\n\n---\n\nTitle: YEбә’IRAH, SEFER - JewishEncyclopedia.com\nURL: https://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/13386-sefer-yezirah\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nits turn, by the prototypes of the three primordial substances when they became realities. Simultaneously with the prototypes, or at least before the real world, space was produced, and it is here conceived as the three dimensions with their opposite directions. The spirit of God, the three primordial elements, and the six dimensions of space form the \"ten Sefirot,\" which, like the spirit of God, exist only ideally, being \"ten Sefirot without reality\" as the text designates them. Their name is possibly derived from the fact that as numbers express only the relations of two objects to each other, so the ten Sefirot are only abstractions and not realities. Again, as the numbers from two to ten are derived from the number one, so the ten Sefirot are derived from one, the spirit of God. The spirit of God, however, is not only the commencement but also the conclusion of the Sefirot, \"their end being in their beginning and their beginning in their end, even as the flame is connected with the coal\"(i. 7). Hence the Sefirot must not be conceived as emanations in the ordinary sense of the word, but rather as modifications of the spirit of God, which first changes to, then becomes water, and finally fire, the last being no further removed from God than the first. Besides these abstract ten Sefirot, which are conceived only ideally, the twenty-two letters of the alphabet produced the material world, for they are real, and are the formative powers of all existence and development. By means of these elements the actual creation of the world took place, and the ten Sefirot, which before this had only an ideal existence, became realities. This is, then, a modified form of the Talmudic doctrine that God created heaven and earth by means of letters (Ber. 58a). The explanation on this point is very obscure, however, since the relation of the twenty-two letters to the ten Sefirot is not clearly defined. The first sentence of the book reads: \"Thirty-two paths, marvels of wisdom, hath God engraved . . . ,\" these paths being then explained as the ten Sefirot and the twenty-two letters. While the Sefirot are expressly designated as \"abstracts\" (), it is said of the letters: \"Twenty-two letters: He drew them, hewed them, combined them, weighed them, interchanged them, and through them produced the whole creation and everything that is destined to come into being\" (ii. 2). The basal theory of the letters apparently regards them neither as independent substances nor yet as mere forms, so that they are, as it were, the connecting-link between essence and form. They are designated, therefore, as the instruments by which the real world, which consists of essence and form, was produced from the Sefirot, which are merely formless essences.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Sefer Yetzirah\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sefer_Yezirah\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nBy thirty-two mysterious paths of wisdom Yah has engraved [all things], [who is] the Lord of hosts, the God of Israel, the living God, the Almighty God, He that is uplifted and exalted, He that Dwells forever, and whose Name is holy; having created His world by three [derivatives] of [the Hebrew root-word] sefar : namely, sefer (a book), sefor (a count) and sippur (a story), along with ten calibrations of empty space and twenty-two letters [of the Hebrew alphabet], [of which] three are principal [letters] (i.e. Чҗ Чһ Ч©вҖҺ), seven are double-sounding [consonants] (i.e. Ч‘Ч’\"Ч“ ЧӣЧӨЧЁ\"ЧӘвҖҺ) and twelve are ordinary [letters] (i.e. Ч” Ч• Ч– Ч— Чҳ Чҷ Чң Ч  ЧЎ Чў ЧҰ Ч§вҖҺ).\n[...]\nThe Sefer Yetzirah describes how the universe was created by the \"God of Israel\" (a list of all of God's Hebrew names appears in the first sentence of the book) through \"32 wondrous ways of wisdom\":\n[...]\nThe book describes the method for using the ten sefirot and the 22 Hebrew letters to gain Divine Insight/Secret using Abraham's tongue. God's covenant with Abraham is described as being twofold.\n[...]\nBesides these three\n[...]\n,\" a distinction\n[...]\nhave two different\n[...]\n, and the\n[...]\nwhich represent only one\n[...]\npossibly derived from\n[...]\nderived from one\n[...]\nsense of the\n[...]\n, but rather as modifications of\n[...]\n, then becomes\n[...]\nSefer Yet\n[...]\nBesides these abstract ten sefirot\n[...]\nare conceived only\n[...]\n, the twenty-two letters of the alphabet produced\n[...]\nmaterial world, for they are real, and are\n[...]\nformative powers of all existence and development. By means of these elements the actual creation of\n[...]\ntook place, and the ten sefirot\n[...]\nwhich before this had only an ideal existence, became realities. This is, then, a modified form of the Talmudic doctrine that God created heaven and earth by means of letters (Berakhot 58a). The explanation on this point is obscure since the relation of the twenty-two letters to the ten sefirot is not clearly defined.\n[...]\nThe first sentence of the book reads: \"Thirty-two paths, marvels of wisdom, hath God engraved...,\" these paths being then explained as the ten sefirot and the twenty-two letters. While the sefirot are expressly designated as \"abstracts\", it is said of the letters: \"Twenty-two letters: God drew them, hewed them, combined them, weighed them, interchanged them, and through them produced the whole creation and everything that is destined to come into being\" (ii. 2).\n[...]\nIn 2002, American mathematician Robert P. C. de Marrais named the pathions, or the 3\n[...]\n-dimensional hypercomplex numbers, after the 32 paths of wisdom in the Sefer Yetzirah.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Sefer Yetzirah and the 32 Paths of Creation | Mayim Achronim\nURL: https://www.mayimachronim.com/sefer-yetzirah-and-the-32-paths-of-creation/\nPublished: 2015-10-08T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: Efraim Palvanov\nHighlights:\nAlong with the 22 letters were the Ten Sefirot, divine energies that imbue everything within Creation. These Sefirot are sometimes said to parallel the 10 base numerical digits, from 0 to 9 (the word sefirah also means вҖңcountingвҖқ). Just as modern physicists might argue that the entire universe can be reduced to mathematical equations, Sefer Yetzirah reduces all of Creation down to these foundational numbers and letters. And so, Sefer Yetzirah begins by stating that God created the universe through lamed-beit netivot, thirty-two paths.\n[...]\nWhere exactly are the 32 Paths of Creation derived from? A careful analysis of the Genesis text shows that God (Elohim) is mentioned 32 times in the account of creation. Each of these 32 parallels the 32 paths. There are ten cases where the Torah says vayomer Elohim, вҖңAnd God saidвҖҰвҖқ in the first chapter. These 10 correspond to the Ten Sefirot. The remaining 22 mentions of God correspond to the 22 letters in the following way:\n[...]\nSefer Yetzirah breaks down the Hebrew alphabet into three groups: the вҖңmothersвҖқ (imaвҖҷot), the вҖңdoublesвҖқ (kefulot), and the вҖңelementalsвҖқ (peshutot). There are three mother letters: Aleph (Чҗ), Mem (Чһ), and Shin (Ч©). These are the вҖңmothersвҖқ because each is associated with one of the three primordial elements of Creation: Aleph is the root of air (avir, ЧҗЧ•ЧҷЧЁ), Mem is the root of water (mayim, ЧһЧҷЧқ), and Shin is the root of fire (esh, ЧҗЧ©). These three correspond to the three times that the Torah says вҖңGod madeвҖқ (Genesis 1:7, 16, and 25).\n[...]\nThe вҖңTree of LifeвҖқ depicting the Ten Sefirot, intertwined by the 22 Letters of the Hebrew Alphabet. Together, they make up the 32 Paths of Wisdom.\n[...]\nFinally, all of these are embedded in the most famous of Kabbalistic diagrams, the Etz Chaim, вҖңTree of LifeвҖқ. The 10 circles on the diagram correspond to the Ten Sefirot. The Sefirot are interconnected by 22 lines, corresponding to the 22 letters. There are three horizontal lines, corresponding to the three mother letters; seven vertical lines, corresponding to the seven doubled letters; and twelve diagonal lines, corresponding to the twelve elemental letters. This simple diagram amazingly captures a great deal of information, and is a key tool in KabbalahвҖ”as well as the first step towards creating your very own calf!\n\n---\n\nTitle: Text of \"Sefer Yetzirah\" Chapter 1\nURL: https://www.emol.org/kabbalah/seferyetzirah/text/index.html\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nWith 32 wonderous ways of wisdom, YAH, the Lord of Hosts, the Gd of Israel, the Living GD (El SHADAI), Omnipotent GD, extolled, Dweller up above whose habitation is eternity. His Name high and holy engraved His name, covenanted, drilled, and created his universe in 32 mysterious paths of wisdom through 3 Sepharim;\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Tree of Life вҖ” Interactive Map of the 10 Sephirot & 22 Paths | Cosmos Daily\nURL: https://cosmosdaily.co/tree-of-life\nPublished: 2026-05-10T08:22:46.000Z\nAuthor: Cosmos Daily\nHighlights:\nThe Tree of Life is the central diagram of Kabbalistic mysticism. Ten sephirot вҖ” emanations of the divine вҖ” are arranged in a specific geometric pattern, connected by twenty-two paths. Together they map the entire architecture of consciousness: from pure undifferentiated being at the top (Kether, the Crown) down through every stage of manifestation to the physical world at the bottom (Malkuth, the Kingdom).\n[...]\nThe tradition originates in medieval Jewish mysticism, was systematized by Isaac Luria in 16th-century Safed\n[...]\nand reached its modern form in the Hermetic Qabalah of the late-19th-century Golden Dawn вҖ” where it was integrated with Tarot, Western astrology, and ceremonial magic into the unified system that Cosmos Daily uses.\n[...]\nEvery sephirah\n[...]\n, virtue, and vice. Every path\n[...]\na Hebrew letter and a Tarot card. To\n[...]\nback to cosmos.\n[...]\nThe 22 paths connect the sephirot. Each carries a letter of the Hebrew alphabet and a Tarot Major Arcana вҖ” and twelve of them are also assigned to the twelve zodiac signs. When your Sun, Moon, and Ascendant fall on these paths, they become illuminated in your chart.\n[...]\nThe Tree of Life has two parallel histories: a Jewish Kabbalistic tradition that runs from the Sefer Yetzirah (3rdвҖ“6th century) through the Zohar (13th century) to the Lurianic synthesis of 16th-century Safed; and a Hermetic Qabalistic tradition that emerged in the late 19th century when the Golden Dawn вҖ” Mathers, Westcott, Regardie, Crowley, Dion Fortune вҖ” wove the Tree together with Tarot, Western astrology, and Hermetic alchemy into the unified esoteric framework that Cosmos Daily inherits.\n[...]\nThe Tree of Life is the central diagram of Kabbalistic mysticism вҖ” 10 sephirot connected by 22 paths, mapping the architecture of consciousness from pure being (Kether) down to the manifest world (Malkuth). It originates in medieval Jewish mysticism and was systematized in Western esotericism by the late-19th-century Golden Dawn.\n[...]\nThe 22 paths connect the 10 sephirot. Each path corresponds to one of the 22 letters of the Hebrew alphabet and one of the 22 Tarot Major Arcana. In Hermetic Qabalah, twelve of these paths are also assigned to the twelve zodiac signs вҖ” meaning your Sun, Moon, and Ascendant each illuminate a specific path on the Tree.\n[...]\nJewish Kabbalah is the original mystical tradition of Judaism, rooted in texts like the Zohar (13th century) and the work of Isaac Luria (16th century). Hermetic Qabalah (note the \"Q\" spelling) is the Western esoteric adaptation developed by the Golden Dawn вҖ” it integrates Tarot, Western astrology, alchemy, and ceremonial magic with the Tree of Life. Cosmos Daily uses the Hermetic Qabalah framework.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Sefirot\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sefirot\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nalshelut\n[...]\nЧЎЦөЧ“Ц¶ЧЁ Ч”ЦҙЧ©Ц°ЧҒЧӘЦ·ЦјЧңЦ°Ч©Ц°\n[...]\ndescending sequence of\n[...]\nAlternative configurations of the sefirot are interpreted by various schools in the historical evolution of Kabbalah, with each articulating differing spiritual aspects. The tradition of enumerating 10 is stated in the Sefer Yetzirah: \"Ten sefirot of nothingness, ten and not nine, ten and not eleven\". As altogether eleven sefirot are listed across the various schemes, two (Keter and Da'at) are seen as unconscious and conscious manifestations of the same principle, conserving the 10 categories. The sefirot are described as channels of divine creative life force or consciousness through which the unknowable divine essence is revealed to humankind.\n[...]\nThe original reference to the sefirot is found in the ancient Sefer Yetzirah\"The Book of Formation,\" attributed to the first Jewish patriarch, Abraham. However, the names of the sefirot as given in later Kabbalah are not specified there, but rather are only identified by their attributes \"forward,\" \"backward,\" \"right,\" \"left,\" \"down,\" \"up,\" \"light,\" \"darkness,\" \"good\" and \"evil.\" Further references to the sefirot, now with their later-accepted names, are elaborated on in the medieval Kabbalistic text of the Zohar, which is one of the core texts of Kabbalah.\n[...]\n16th-century rational synthesis of\n[...]\nbalah, the\n[...]\n4 Chesed - \"\n[...]\n\" 5 Gevurah - \"Discipline\" 6 Tiferet - \"Glory\" (Secondary emotions:) 7 Netzach - \"Victory\" 8 Hod - \"Splendour\" 9 Yesod - \"Foundation\" (Vessel to bring action:) 10 Malkuth - \"Kingdom\" Kingship\n[...]\nThese ten levels are associated with Kabbalah's four different \"Worlds\" or planes of existence, the main part from the perspective of the descending \"chain of progression\" (Seder hishtalshelut), that links the infinite divine Ein Sof with the finite, physical realm. In all Worlds, the 10 sefirot radiate, and are the divine channels through which every level is continuously created from nothing. Since they are the attributes through which the unknowable, infinite divine essence becomes revealed to the creations, all ten emanate in each World. Nonetheless, the structure of the Four Worlds arises because in each one, certain sefirot predominate. Each World is spiritual, apart from the lower aspect of the final World, which is the Asiyah Gashmi (\"Physical Asiyah\"), the physical Universe. Each World is progressively grosser and further removed from consciousness of the Divine, until in this World it is possible to be unaware of or to deny God. In descending order:\n[...]\n3. World of Formation (Hebrew: ЧҷЦ°ЧҰЦҙЧҷЧЁЦёЧ”, Yetzirah): On this level, creation is related to form. The Divine emotional sefirot of Chesed to Yesod predominate.","_meta":{"searchTime":1645.8}}]}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_4epe5vc9l6nm_2","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Kabbalistic Astrology: Sephirot, Planets, Hebrew Letters & Zodiac Correspondences - Kabbalistic Numerology Explained Kabbalistic Astrology: Sephirot & Planetary Correspondences\nURL: https://kabbalisticnumerology.org/kabbalistic-astrology-sephirot-planets/\nPublished: 2025-12-02T23:32:31.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn classical Kabbalistic tradition, the Hebrew alphabet and the Tree of Life form a symbolic map of creation. Later commentators correlated these symbols with astrology, the zodiac and the seven classical planets. It is important to note that the original Kabbalah predates the discovery of Uranus, Neptune and Pluto, so the planetary system was based on the traditional seven luminaries visible to the naked eye: Sun, Moon, Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn.\n[...]\nKabbalistic Astrology weaves together the Tree of Life, the Hebrew alphabet and the movements of the heavens. Unlike modern systems that include Uranus and Neptune, classical Kabbalah aligns the sephirot with the seven visible planets and the zodiac signs described in the Sefer Yetzirah. This creates a symbolic map where divine energies flow through planetary forces, Hebrew letters and celestial qualities. Below you will find the historically accurate correspondences used in traditional Kabbalistic and early esoteric teachings.\n[...]\n- Kether (Crown) вҖ” Transcendent Principle Not assigned to any planet. Kether represents the primordial divine source beyond the celestial spheres.\n[...]\n- Chokhmah (Wisdom) вҖ” Zodiac / Fixed Stars Often linked to the вҖңmazalotвҖқ (the starry heavens), not a single planet.\n[...]\n- Binah (Understanding) вҖ” Saturn\n[...]\n- Chesed (Mercy / Wisdom in action) вҖ” Jupiter\n[...]\n- Gevurah (Strength / Judgement) вҖ” Mars\n[...]\n- Tiferet (Beauty / Harmony) вҖ” Sun\n[...]\n- Netzach (Victory / Endurance) вҖ” Venus\n- Hod (Splendour / Intellect) вҖ” Mercury\n[...]\n- Yesod (Foundation / Channeling) вҖ” Moon\n- Malkhut (Kingdom / Manifestation) вҖ” Earth Represents the physical world.\n[...]\nThe paths of the Tree of Life connect the sefirot and correspond to the 22 Hebrew letters. According to traditional standard Hermetic-Kabbalistic use of the Sefer Yetzirah classifications, the 12 вҖңsimple lettersвҖқ align with the 12 zodiac signs.\n[...]\n- Netzach вҶ’ Malkhut вҖ” Ч§ (Qof) вҖ” Pisces\n[...]\n- Netzach вҶ’ Yesod вҖ” ЧҰ (Tzadi) вҖ” Aries\n[...]\n- Hod вҶ’ Tiferet вҖ” Чў (Ayin) вҖ” Capricorn\n[...]\n- Gevurah вҶ’ Chesed вҖ” Чҳ (Tet) вҖ” Leo\n[...]\n- Binah вҶ’ Tiferet вҖ” Ч– (Zayin) вҖ” Gemini\n[...]\n- Chokhmah вҶ’ Tiferet вҖ” Ч” (Heh) вҖ” Aquarius\n[...]\n- Tiferet вҶ’ Chesed вҖ” Чҷ (Yod) вҖ” Virgo\n[...]\n- Tiferet вҶ’ Netzach вҖ” Ч  (Nun) вҖ” Scorpio\n[...]\n- Chokhmah вҶ’ Chesed вҖ” Ч• (Vav) вҖ” Taurus\n[...]\n- Binah вҶ’ Gevurah вҖ” Ч— (Chet) вҖ” Cancer\n[...]\n- Tiferet вҶ’ Gevurah вҖ” Чң (Lamed) вҖ” Libra\n[...]\nYes. Classical Kabbalistic astrology uses the seven visible planetsвҖ”Sun, Moon, Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter and SaturnвҖ”to correspond to the lower sephirot. Kether and Chokhmah remain transcendent and are not assigned modern planets.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Principal Qabalistic Correspondences\nURL: http://www.erwinhessle.com/resources/qabcorr.php\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n| Choose Column One: | (none) Col. II\n[...]\nCol. III вҖ”\n[...]\n. VII вҖ” Astrological Col. VIII вҖ” Qliphoth (Hebrew) Col\n[...]\nXIII вҖ” Se\n[...]\nYetzirah\n[...]\nThe Tree of Life\n[...]\n. XIV вҖ” General Tarot Attributions\n[...]\n. XV вҖ” King Scale of Colour Col. XVI вҖ” Queen Scale of Colour Col. XVII вҖ” Emperor Scale of Colour Col. XVIII вҖ”\n[...]\nCol. XXXIV вҖ” Greek\n[...]\nCXXIII вҖ” Qliphoth (English) Col. CXX вҖ” Magical Images of the\n[...]\nphiroth Col. CLXXX вҖ” Titles of Tarot Trumps Col. CLXXXI вҖ” Correct Designs of Tarot Trumps Col. CLXXV вҖ” Hebrew Letters Col. CLXXVI вҖ” Numerical Value Col. CLXXXII вҖ” The Human Body Col. CLXXXIII вҖ” Legendary Orders of Being Col. CLXXXVI вҖ” Diseases (Typical) |\n[...]\n| Key | Col. II | Col. III | Col. VII |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| 1 | Kether вҖ” ЧӣЧӘЧЁ | Crown | Sphere of Primum Mobile |\n| 2 | Chokmah вҖ” Ч—ЧӣЧһЧ” | Wisdom | Sphere of the Zodiac |\n| 3 | Binah вҖ” Ч‘ЧҷЧ Ч” | Understanding | Sphere of Saturn |\n| 4 | Chesed вҖ” Ч—ЧЎЧ“ | Mercy | Sphere of Jupiter |\n| 5 | Geburah вҖ” Ч’Ч‘Ч•ЧЁЧ” | Strength | Sphere of Mars |\n| 6 | Tiphareth вҖ” ЧӘЧӨЧҗЧЁЧӘ | Beauty | Sphere of Sol |\n| 7 | Netzach вҖ” Ч ЧҰЧ— | Victory | Sphere of Venus |\n| 8 | Hod вҖ” Ч”Ч•Ч“ | Splendour | Sphere of Mercury |\n| 9 | Yesod вҖ” ЧҷЧЎЧ•Ч“ | Foundation | Sphere of Luna |\n| 10 | Malkuth вҖ” ЧһЧңЧӣЧ•ЧӘ | Kingdom | Sphere of the Elements |\n| 11 | Aleph вҖ” ЧҗЧңЧЈ | Ox | Air |\n| 12 | Beth вҖ” Ч‘ЧҷЧӘ | House | Mercury |\n| 13 | Gimel вҖ” Ч’ЧһЧң | Camel | Luna |\n| 14 | Daleth вҖ” Ч“ЧңЧӘ | Door | Venus |\n| 15 | HГ© вҖ” Ч”Ч” | Window | Aries |\n| 16 | Vau вҖ” Ч•Ч• | Nail | Taurus |\n| 17 | Zain вҖ” Ч–ЧҷЧҹ | Sword | Gemini |\n| 18 | Cheth вҖ” Ч—ЧҷЧӘ | Fence | Cancer |\n| 19 | Teth вҖ” ЧҳЧҷЧӘ | Serpent | Leo |\n| 20 | Yod вҖ” ЧҷЧ•Ч“ | Hand | Virgo |\n| 21 | Kaph вҖ” ЧӣЧЈ | Palm | Jupiter |\n| 22 | Lamed вҖ” ЧңЧһЧ“ | Ox Goad | Libra |\n| 23 | Maim вҖ” ЧһЧҷЧқ | Water | Water |\n| 24 | Nun вҖ” Ч Ч•Чҹ | Fish | Scorpio |\n| 25 | Samekh вҖ” ЧЎЧһЧҡ | Prop | Sagittarius |\n| 26 | Ayin вҖ” ЧўЧҷЧҹ | Eye | Capricornus |\n| 27 | PГ© вҖ” ЧӨЧ” | Mouth | Mars |\n| 28 | Tzaddi вҖ” ЧҰЧ“Чҷ | Fish-hook | Aquarius |\n| 29 | Qoph вҖ” Ч§Ч•ЧЈ | Back of Head | Pisces |\n| 30 | Resh вҖ” ЧЁЧҷЧ© | Head | Sol |\n| 31 | Shin вҖ” Ч©ЧҷЧҹ | Tooth | Fire |\n| 32 | Tau вҖ” ЧӘЧ• | Tau (as Egyptian) | Saturn |\n| 32 bis | вҖ” | вҖ” | Earth |\n| 31 bis | вҖ” | вҖ” | Spirit |\n[...]\n- Column CXXIII, Qliphoth (English) вҖ” English names of Sephirotic Qliphoth taken from Column CXXIII, names of other Qliphoth taken from notes to Column VIII\n- Column XIV, General Tarot Attributions вҖ” titles changed for consistency with The Book of Thoth; suit and court card dual attributions removed from Trumps\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Complete Correspondence Tables: Your Reference Guide | Unified System\n вҖ“ Nicole's ritual universe\nURL: https://mysticryst.com/ms/blogs/the-mystic-journal/complete-correspondence-tables-reference-guide\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThis is your complete reference guideвҖ”the master tables of ALL correspondences between Tarot, Astrology, and Kabbalah. Everything we've explored in this series is compiled here in organized, accessible tables. Bookmark this article. Print it. Keep it by your Tarot deck, your astrology books, your meditation space. This is your ROSETTA STONE for the unified systemвҖ”the key that unlocks the connections between all three traditions. When you draw a Tarot card, you can instantly see its Hebrew letter, its astrological correspondence, its path on the Tree. When you study a planetary transit, you can immediately find its Sephirah, its Tarot card, its transformative meaning. This is the complete map, the full integration, the unified wisdom in tabular form. Use it. Reference it. Let it guide your practice.\n[...]\nThe 10\n[...]\n| Sephirah | Number | Hebrew | Meaning | Planet | Color | Archangel | Divine Name |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n[...]\n| Keter | 1 | ЧӣЧӘЧЁ | Crown | Neptune/Primum Mobile | Brilliant White | Metatron | Ehyeh (I Am) |\n[...]\n| Chokmah | 2 | Ч—ЧӣЧһЧ” | Wisdom | Uranus/Zodiac | Grey | Raziel | Yah |\n[...]\n| Binah | 3 | Ч‘ЧҷЧ Ч” | Understanding | Saturn | Black | Tzaphkiel | YHVH Elohim |\n[...]\n| Chesed | 4 | Ч—ЧЎЧ“ | Mercy | Jupiter | Blue | Tzadkiel | El |\n[...]\n| Geburah | 5 | Ч’Ч‘Ч•ЧЁЧ” | Severity | Mars | Red | Kamael | Elohim Gibor |\n[...]\n| Tiphareth | 6 | ЧӘЧӨЧҗЧЁЧӘ | Beauty | Sun | Gold/Yellow | Michael |\n[...]\n| Path | Connects | Tarot | Hebrew Letter | Value | Astrology | Element/Planet/Sign |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| 11 | Keter вҶ’ Chokmah | 0 - The Fool | Aleph Чҗ | 1 | Air | Element |\n[...]\n| 12 | Keter вҶ’ Binah | I - The Magician | Beth Ч‘ | 2 | Mercury вҳҝ | Planet |\n[...]\n| 13 | Keter вҶ’ Tiphareth | II - High Priestess | Gimel Ч’ | 3 | Moon вҳҪ | Planet |\n[...]\n| 14 | Chokmah вҶ’ Binah | III - The Empress | Daleth Ч“ | 4 | Venus вҷҖ | Planet |\n[...]\n| 15 | Chokmah вҶ’ Tiphareth | IV - The Emperor | Heh Ч” | 5 | Aries вҷҲ | Sign |\n[...]\n| 16 | Chokmah вҶ’ Chesed | V - The Hierophant | Vav Ч• | 6 | Taurus вҷү | Sign |\n[...]\n| 17 | Binah вҶ’ Tiphareth | VI - The Lovers | Zayin Ч– | 7 | Gemini вҷҠ | Sign |\n[...]\n| 18 | Binah вҶ’ Geburah | VII - The Chariot | Cheth Ч— | 8 | Cancer вҷӢ | Sign |\n[...]\nFor Kabbalah Study:1. Choose a Sephirah from Table 12. Note its planetary correspondence3. Find all paths connected to it in Table 24. Study the Tarot cards for those paths5. Understand the Sephirah through its connections\n[...]\nform: These tables prove that Tarot, Astrology,\n[...]\nletter and a planet/sign. Every path connects\n[...]\nEvery correspondence is structural,\n[...]\n. The tables are the proof. The integration is complete. The system is\n\n---\n\nTitle: Appendix V\nURL: https://www.thelemistas.org/en/Documents/Crowley/MTP/mtp_app05\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n# A few of the Principal Correspondencesof the QabalahReprinted with additions from777\n[...]\n| IKEY\n[...]\n& LETTERS | IIIENGLISH OF COLUMN II | VITHE HEAVENS OF ASSIAH | VIIENGLISH OF COLUMN VI | IXTHE SWORDANDTHE SERPENT | XIELEMENTS (WITHTHEIR PLANETARYRULERS)Do not confuse withrulers of Zodiac | XIITHE TREE OF LIFE |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n[...]\n| 1 | ЧӣЧӘЧЁ | Crown | ЧЁЧҗЧ©ЧҷЧӘ Ч”Ч’ЧңЧ’ЧңЧҷЧқ | Sphere of the Primum Mobile | The Flaming Sword follows the downward course of the Sephiroth, and is compared to the Lightning Flash. Its hilt is in Kether and its point in Malkuth. | Root of | 1st Plane Middle Pillar |\n[...]\n| 2 | Ч—ЧӣЧһЧ” | Wisdom. | ЧһЧЎЧңЧ•ЧӘ | Sphere of the ZodiacFixed Stars | Root of | 2nd Plane Right Pillar |\n[...]\n| 3 | Ч‘ЧҷЧ Ч” | Understanding. | Ч©Ч‘ЧӘЧҗЧҷ | Sphere of Saturn | Root of | 2nd Plane Left Pillar |\n[...]\n| 4 | Ч—ЧЎЧ“ | Mercy. | ЧҰЧ“Ч§ | Sphere of Jupiter | Root of | 3rd Plane Right Pillar |\n[...]\n| 5 | Ч’Ч‘Ч•ЧЁЧ” | Strength. | ЧһЧҗЧ“ЧҷЧқ | Sphere of Mars | Root of | 3rd Plane Left Pillar |\n[...]\n| 6 | ЧӘЧӨЧҗЧЁЧӘ | Beauty | Ч©ЧһЧ© | Sphere of Sol | Root of | 4th Plane Middle Pillar |\n[...]\n| 7 | Ч ЧҰЧ— | Victory | Ч Ч•Ч’Ч” | Sphere of Venus | Root of | 5th Plane Right Pillar |\n[...]\n| 8 | Ч”Ч•Ч“ | Splendour | ЧӣЧ•ЧӣЧ‘ | Sphere of Mercury | Root of | 5th Plane Left Pillar |\n[...]\n| 9 | ЧҷЧЎЧ•Ч“ | Foundation | ЧңЧ‘Ч Ч” | Sphere of Luna | Root of | 6th Plane Middle Pillar |\n[...]\n| 10 | ЧһЧңЧӣЧ•ЧӘ ЧҷЧЎЧ•Ч“Ч•ЧӘ | Kingdom | Ч—ЧңЧқ | Sphere of the Elements | Root of | 7th Plane Middle Pillar |\n[...]\n| 11 | ЧҗЧңЧЈ | Ox | ЧЁЧ•Ч— | Air | The Serpent of Wisdom follows the course of the paths or letters upward, its head being thus in ЧҗвҖҺ, its tail in ЧӘвҖҺ. ЧҗвҖҺ, ЧһвҖҺ, & Ч©вҖҺ are the Mother letters, referring to the Elements; Ч‘вҖҺ, Ч’вҖҺ, Ч“вҖҺ, ЧӣвҖҺ, ЧӨвҖҺ, ЧЁвҖҺ and ЧӘвҖҺ, the Double letters, to the Planets; the rest, Single letters, to the Zodiac. | Hot and Moist | Path joins 1-2 |\n[...]\n| 12 | Ч‘ЧҷЧӘ | House | (Planets following Sephiroth corresponding) | Mercury | . . . . . | Path joins 1-3 |\n[...]\n| 17 | Ч–ЧҷЧҹ | Sword | ЧӘЧҗЧ•ЧһЧҷЧқ | Gemini | Path joins 3-6 |\n[...]\n18 | Ч—ЧҷЧӘ | Fence | ЧЎЧЁЧҳЧҹ | Cancer | Path joins 3-5 |\n[...]\n| IKEY SCALE | XIVGENERAL ATTRIBUTIONOF TAROT | XVTHE KING SCALEOF COLOUR | XIXSELECTION OFEGYPTIAN GODS | XXIISMALL SELECTIONOF H\n[...]\n| IKEY SCALE | LXXVIITHE PLANETS AND THEIR NUMBERS | LXXXIMETALS | LXXXIIITHE ATTRIBUTION OF THE HEXAGRAM |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| 12 | 8 | Mercury | Left Lower Point |\n| 13 | 9 | Silver | Bottom Point |\n| 14 | 7 | Copper | Right Lower Point |\n| 21 | 4 | Tin | Right Upper Point |\n| 27 | 5 | Iron | Left Upper Point |\n| 30 | 6 | Gold | Centre Point |\n| 31 | 3 | Lead | Top Point |\n\n---\n\nTitle: Tree of Life in Kabbalah: The Ten Sephiroth Explained\nURL: https://thalira.com/blogs/quantum-codex/tree-of-life-kabbalah-guide\nPublished: 2026-03-19T08:22:49.000Z\nAuthor: Thalira Research Team  | Reviewed for accuracy and spiritual depth\nHighlights:\nfrom infinite to finite.\n[...]\n- Three pillars: The Tree is organized into the Pillar of Mercy (active, expansive), the Pillar of Severity (receptive, contracting), and the Pillar of Equilibrium (balanced center).\n[...]\n- Twenty-two paths: The connections between Sephiroth correspond to the twenty-two letters of the Hebrew alphabet and, in the Golden Dawn tradition, to the tarot Major Arcana.\n[...]\nThe Pillar of Mercy (right side): Chokmah, Chesed, Netzach. This pillar represents the active, expansive, masculine principle. In Freemasonry, it is called Jachin. Its\n[...]\nThe Pillar of Equilibrium (center): Kether, Tiphareth, Yesod, Malkuth. This pillar represents the balanced\n[...]\nIn the late 19th century, the Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn systematized a correspondence between the twenty-two paths, the twenty-two letters, and the twenty-two Major Arcana cards of the tarot. This system, developed by MacGregor Mathers, Wynn Westcott, and others, has become the standard in Western esotericism, though it differs in some assignments from traditional Jewish Kabbalistic attributions.\n[...]\nIn the Golden Dawn system, each Major Arcana card is assigned to a specific path on the Tree. The Fool (0) is assigned to the path between Kether and Chokmah. The Magician (I) to the path between Kether and Binah. The High Priestess (II) to the path between Kether and Tiphareth. And so on through The World (XXI) on the path between Yesod and Malkuth. This system means that a tarot reading can be mapped onto the Tree, and that \"pathworking,\" the practice of meditating on each path in sequence, can use the tarot images as guides for contemplation. The system is elegant and internally consistent, though readers should be aware that different traditions assign the cards differently.\n[...]\nThe third was the Golden Dawn synthesis of the late 19th century, which combined the Tree with tarot, astrology, Enochian magic, and ceremonial practice into a comprehensive system of initiation. This synthesis, through the published writings of Aleister Crowley, Dion Fortune, and Israel Regardie, became the dominant form of the Tree of Life in English-speaking esotericism. Manly P. Hall's treatment of Kabbalistic symbolism in The Secret Teachings of All Ages draws on all three of these streams.\n[...]\nEach of the twenty-two paths connecting the Sephiroth corresponds to one of the twenty-two letters of the Hebrew alphabet. In the Sefer Yetzirah, these letters are described as the creative instruments through which God formed the world. The Golden Dawn tradition further assigned a tarot Major Arcana card to each path, creating a correspondence system linking Kabbalah, tarot, and astrology that remains the standard in Western esotericism.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Thelemapedia: The Encyclopedia of Thelema & Magick | Tree of Life:Astrology\nURL: http://www.thelemapedia.org/index.php/Tree_of_Life:Astrology\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Tree of Life includes The 10 Emanations or Sephiroth The 22 Paths that connect them The Correspondences\n[...]\nWithin the western magical tradition, the Tree of Life is used as a kind of conceptual filing cabinet within the larger system of the Qabalah, the use of which was central to the mystical teachings of Aleister Crowley. Each sephera (\"Emination\") and path is assigned various ideas, such as astrological planets and signs, cards of the Tarot, and the classical elements. Many of these correspondances were gathered together in Crowley's book Liber 777, which is used for these listings.\n[...]\n### The Ten Sephiroth\n[...]\nThe Sephiroth are represented not so much by the planets themselves, but the spheres that contain them. In the classical system of Aristotle(384-322 BCE), the Earth was at the center of the Cosmos, and was made up of the four fundamental elementsвҖ”air, earth, fire, and water. This is represented in Malkuth, the tenth and lowest emanation on the Tree. The Earth was surrounded by concentric, spherical shells of aether. Seven spheres were the home of the planets. The eighth sphere was home to the \"fixed stars\" (which contains the Zodiac), and the outermost was the Primum Mobile or \"Prime Mover\", which gave motion to all the other spheres.\n[...]\n- 1 KetherвҖ”ЧЁЧҗЧ©ЧҷЧӘ Ч”Ч’ЧңЧ’ЧңЧҷЧқ Rashith ha-GilgalimвҖ”Sphere of the Primum Mobile(represented by Pluto)\n- 2 ChokmahвҖ”ЧһЧ–ЧңЧ•ЧӘ MazlothвҖ”Sphere of the Fixed Stars (represented by Neptune)\n- 3 BinahвҖ”Ч©Ч‘ЧӘЧҗЧҷ ShabbathaiвҖ”Sphere of Saturn\n- 4 ChesedвҖ”ЧҰЧ“Ч§ TzedeqвҖ”Sphere of Jupiter\n- 5 GeburahвҖ”ЧһЧҗЧ“ЧҷЧқ MadimвҖ”Sphere of Mars\n- 6 TipharethвҖ”Ч©ЧһЧ© ShemeshвҖ”Sphere of Sol\n- 7 NetzachвҖ”Ч Ч’Ч” NogahвҖ”Sphere of Venus\n- 8 HodвҖ”ЧӣЧ•ЧӣЧ‘ KokabвҖ”Sphere of Mercury\n- 9 YesodвҖ”ЧңЧ‘Ч Ч” LevanahвҖ”Sphere of Luna\n- 10 MalkuthвҖ”Ч—ЧңЧқ ЧҷЧЎЧ•Ч“Ч•ЧӘ Cholem YesodothвҖ”Sphere of the Elements(represented by Earth)\n[...]\nof HГ©вҖ”ЧӘ\n[...]\nTelehвҖ” Aries(ruled by Mars; planet exalted: Sol)\n[...]\n16 Path of VauвҖ”\n[...]\nSharвҖ” Taurus(ruled by Venus; planet exalted: Luna)\n[...]\n- 17 Path of ZainвҖ”ЧӘЧҗ\n[...]\nTeonim вҖ” Gemini(ruled by Mercury)\n[...]\n- 18 Path of ChethвҖ”ЧЎЧЁЧҳЧҹ SartonвҖ” Cancer(ruled by Luna; planet exalted: Jupiter)\n[...]\n- 19 Path of TethвҖ”ЧҗЧЁЧҷЧ” AriвҖ” Leo(ruled by Sol; planet exalted: Uranus)\n[...]\n- 20 Path of YodвҖ”Ч‘ЧӘ\n[...]\nBetulahвҖ” Virgo(ruled by Mercury; planet exalted\n[...]\nnaimвҖ” Libra(ruled by Venus; planet exalted: Saturn)\n[...]\nrabвҖ” Scorpio(ruled by\n[...]\nhethвҖ” Sagittarius(ruled by Jupiter)\n[...]\nGediвҖ” Capricorn(ruled by Saturn; planet exalted:\n[...]\n; planet exalted:\n[...]\nDagimвҖ”\n[...]\nby Jupiter; planet exalted: Venus)\n[...]\nAstrology Decans Astrological Angels Godforms Tarot Colors Elements"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"79e3223a-ba20-4f6e-b874-a03376aa416a","uuid":"dc83578a-cb80-4e0d-b13d-c5925d71f35e","timestamp":"2026-06-10T17:41:25.220Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Kabbalistic Astrology: Sephirot, Planets, Hebrew Letters & Zodiac Correspondences - Kabbalistic Numerology Explained Kabbalistic Astrology: Sephirot & Planetary Correspondences\nURL: https://kabbalisticnumerology.org/kabbalistic-astrology-sephirot-planets/\nPublished: 2025-12-02T23:32:31.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn classical Kabbalistic tradition, the Hebrew alphabet and the Tree of Life form a symbolic map of creation. Later commentators correlated these symbols with astrology, the zodiac and the seven classical planets. It is important to note that the original Kabbalah predates the discovery of Uranus, Neptune and Pluto, so the planetary system was based on the traditional seven luminaries visible to the naked eye: Sun, Moon, Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn.\n[...]\nKabbalistic Astrology weaves together the Tree of Life, the Hebrew alphabet and the movements of the heavens. Unlike modern systems that include Uranus and Neptune, classical Kabbalah aligns the sephirot with the seven visible planets and the zodiac signs described in the Sefer Yetzirah. This creates a symbolic map where divine energies flow through planetary forces, Hebrew letters and celestial qualities. Below you will find the historically accurate correspondences used in traditional Kabbalistic and early esoteric teachings.\n[...]\n- Kether (Crown) вҖ” Transcendent Principle Not assigned to any planet. Kether represents the primordial divine source beyond the celestial spheres.\n[...]\n- Chokhmah (Wisdom) вҖ” Zodiac / Fixed Stars Often linked to the вҖңmazalotвҖқ (the starry heavens), not a single planet.\n[...]\n- Binah (Understanding) вҖ” Saturn\n[...]\n- Chesed (Mercy / Wisdom in action) вҖ” Jupiter\n[...]\n- Gevurah (Strength / Judgement) вҖ” Mars\n[...]\n- Tiferet (Beauty / Harmony) вҖ” Sun\n[...]\n- Netzach (Victory / Endurance) вҖ” Venus\n- Hod (Splendour / Intellect) вҖ” Mercury\n[...]\n- Yesod (Foundation / Channeling) вҖ” Moon\n- Malkhut (Kingdom / Manifestation) вҖ” Earth Represents the physical world.\n[...]\nThe paths of the Tree of Life connect the sefirot and correspond to the 22 Hebrew letters. According to traditional standard Hermetic-Kabbalistic use of the Sefer Yetzirah classifications, the 12 вҖңsimple lettersвҖқ align with the 12 zodiac signs.\n[...]\n- Netzach вҶ’ Malkhut вҖ” Ч§ (Qof) вҖ” Pisces\n[...]\n- Netzach вҶ’ Yesod вҖ” ЧҰ (Tzadi) вҖ” Aries\n[...]\n- Hod вҶ’ Tiferet вҖ” Чў (Ayin) вҖ” Capricorn\n[...]\n- Gevurah вҶ’ Chesed вҖ” Чҳ (Tet) вҖ” Leo\n[...]\n- Binah вҶ’ Tiferet вҖ” Ч– (Zayin) вҖ” Gemini\n[...]\n- Chokhmah вҶ’ Tiferet вҖ” Ч” (Heh) вҖ” Aquarius\n[...]\n- Tiferet вҶ’ Chesed вҖ” Чҷ (Yod) вҖ” Virgo\n[...]\n- Tiferet вҶ’ Netzach вҖ” Ч  (Nun) вҖ” Scorpio\n[...]\n- Chokhmah вҶ’ Chesed вҖ” Ч• (Vav) вҖ” Taurus\n[...]\n- Binah вҶ’ Gevurah вҖ” Ч— (Chet) вҖ” Cancer\n[...]\n- Tiferet вҶ’ Gevurah вҖ” Чң (Lamed) вҖ” Libra\n[...]\nYes. Classical Kabbalistic astrology uses the seven visible planetsвҖ”Sun, Moon, Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter and SaturnвҖ”to correspond to the lower sephirot. Kether and Chokhmah remain transcendent and are not assigned modern planets.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Principal Qabalistic Correspondences\nURL: http://www.erwinhessle.com/resources/qabcorr.php\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n| Choose Column One: | (none) Col. II\n[...]\nCol. III вҖ”\n[...]\n. VII вҖ” Astrological Col. VIII вҖ” Qliphoth (Hebrew) Col\n[...]\nXIII вҖ” Se\n[...]\nYetzirah\n[...]\nThe Tree of Life\n[...]\n. XIV вҖ” General Tarot Attributions\n[...]\n. XV вҖ” King