{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_e75aiccbnjyl_1","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Extracts from the Zohar, Pritzker Edition\nURL: https://supress.sites-pro.stanford.edu/sites/supress/files/media/file/introduction_by_daniel_matt.pdf\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: El Ot, Jerusalem, for Stanford University Press\nHighlights:\nHA-zOHAR\n[...]\nRadiance)'\n[...]\n(Castile)\n[...]\nAramaic,\n[...]\nKabbalah\n[...]\nexceeds\n[...]\nTorah,\n[...]\nDeuteronomy.\n[...]\nGreenвҖҷs\n[...]\nKabbalah\n[...]\nZohar,\n[...]\nText\n\nof\n[...]\nthe\n\nZohar\n[...]\nZohar,\n[...]\nmanuscripts.\n[...]\n(zohar)\n[...]\n12:3:\n\nThe\n[...]\nenlightened\n[...]\nzohar,\n[...]\n[or:\n[...]\nsplendor],\n[...]\n2.\n\nOn\n[...]\nsections\n\nof\n[...]\nthe\n\nZohar,\n[...]\nGershom\n[...]\nScholem,\n[...]\nKabbalah,\n[...]\n214-19;\n[...]\nTishby,\n[...]\nZohar,\n[...]\n1:1вҖ”7.\n[...]\nAramaic,\n[...]\nha-NeвҖҷlam,\n[...]\nAramaic.\n[...]\nTorah,\n[...]\nZohar:\n[...]\nde-Razin,\n[...]\nde-Mishpatim,\n[...]\ndi-Tsni\n[...]\nRabba,\n[...]\nZuta,\n[...]\nMetivta,\n[...]\nYanuga.\n[...]\nha-NeвҖҷlam,\n[...]\nMatnitin,\n[...]\nTosefta,\n[...]\nTorah,\n[...]\nkabbalist,\n[...]\nTranslatorвҖҷs\n[...]\nAramaic\n[...]\nTranslatorвҖҷs\n[...]\nAramaic\n[...]\nReuven\n[...]\nMargaliot\n[...]\nha-Zohar\n[...]\nAramaic\n[...]\nZohar,\n[...]\nAramaic,\n[...]\na\n\nlanguage\n[...]\nSpain.вҖқ>\n[...]\nauthor(s)\n[...]\nconcocted\n[...]\nAramaic\n[...]\nZoharвҖҷs\n[...]\nAramaic,\n[...]\nScholem,\n[...]\nKabbalah,\n[...]\n226вҖ”29;\n[...]\nTishby,\n[...]\nZohar,\n[...]\nTranslatorвҖҷs\n[...]\nAramaic\n[...]\nTorah).\n[...]\nneo-Aramaic\n[...]\nCastilian.\n[...]\nZoharвҖҷs\n[...]\npoetic,\n[...]\nconnotations,\n[...]\nZoharвҖҷs\n[...]\nkabbalists\n[...]\nAramaic,\n[...]\nZohar,\n[...]\nAramaic\n[...]\nfive-volume\n[...]\n(Kabbalah,\n[...]\n241)\n[...]\nkabbalistic\n[...]\nTranslatorвҖҷs\n[...]\nAramaic\n[...]\nAramaic.\n[...]\nTishby\n[...]\nTishby\n\n---\n\nTitle: Moses de LeГіn | Jewish Virtual Library\nURL: https://jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/MosesdeLeon.html\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nMoses ben Shem Tov de LeГіn was a Spanish rabbi and Kabbalist who is believe to be the author of the Zohar.\n[...]\nMoved by an unusual enthusiasm, combined with the urge to counteract the influence of certain rationalistic trends, Moses composed various writings toward the close of the 1270s. He credited ancient scholars and sages as the authors of these works, probably to give them more authority. They were designed to propagate the doctrine of Kabbalism in the pattern in which it had crystallized in his own mind.\n[...]\nCompleted before 1286 they form the Midrash ha-Ne'elam, or \"Mystical Midrash,\" and are the main substance of the Zohar. (The later stratum in this composite work was written by another kabbalist.)\n[...]\nFor a number of years, during the composition of the Zohar, and at least until 1291, he resided in Guadalajara, circulating from his home the first parts of the Zohar, which included a different version of the Midrash ha-Ne'elam.\n[...]\nIn its literary form the Zohar is a collection of several books or sections which include short midrashic statements, longer homilies, and discussions on many topics. Moses De LeГіn credited Shimon bar Yochai as the author, but there are also long anonymous sections.\n[...]\nIn the printed editions the Zohar is composed of five volumes. According to the division in most editions, three of them appear under the name Sefer ha-Zohar al ha-Torah; one volume bears the title Tikkunei ha-Zohar; the fifth, entitled Zohar Chadash, is a collection of sayings and texts found in the manuscripts of the Tzfat kabbalists after the printing of the Zohar.\n[...]\nThe main part of the Zohar is arranged according to the weekly portions of the Torah, up to and including the portion Pinchas, Numbers 29. From Deuteronomy only parts of three Torah portions are included\n[...]\nBasically it is a Kabbalistic Midrash on the Torah, mixed with short statements, long expositions, and narratives concerning Shimon b. Yochai and his companions.\n[...]\nSome of it\n[...]\nThe number of verses interpreted in each portion is relatively small. Often the exposition digresses to other subjects quite divorced from the actual text of the portion, and some of the interpretations are quite skillfully constructed.\n[...]\nMany stories act as a framework for the homilies of the companions: conversations while they are on a journey or when they rest for the night.\n[...]\nThe Zohar became a best-seller, the basic groundwork text for all subsequent Kabbalists.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Zohar\nURL: http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0021_0_21601.html\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nMoses de Leon\n[...]\nthe Zohar\n[...]\nthe Zohar,\n[...]\nmaterial in the Zohar and uses it\n[...]\nproperty. He\n[...]\nexpositions from different parts of the Zohar, adding to them combinations of themes and\n[...]\nexpositions, which are in perfect accord with the zoharic spirit and show that his thinking is\n[...]\nthe Zohar. In many cases his\n[...]\nconstitute an interpretation\n[...]\ndifficult passages of the Zohar which\n[...]\nkabbalists\n[...]\ntrue literary sources\n[...]\nThe long passage\n[...]\nMishkan ha-Edut is written entirely in\n[...]\nparticular Hebrew style\n[...]\nZohar, and\n[...]\nkabbalistic works\n[...]\nMoses de Leon\n[...]\nthe sexual symbolism developed with regard to the relationships between the Sefirot, and the striking interest shown\n[...]\ndemonology and sorcery\n[...]\nno reason to assume\n[...]\nunknown author wrote the Zohar in the lifetime of Moses de Leon, and then passed it on to him. The authorship of Moses de Leon solves the problems raised by an analysis of the Zohar together with his Hebrew works. These books were largely written in order to prepare the ground for the publication of the texts of the Zohar which went hand in hand with this work. In particular, the Mishkan ha-Edut (1293) is full of recommendations\n\n---\n\nTitle: The Zohar - Jewish Theological Seminary\nURL: https://www.jtsa.edu/torah/exploring-kabbalah-episode-4/\nPublished: 2024-04-16T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n, the king of Castile, Alfonso X, known as El Sabio (the wise one) fostered a robust culture of learning and\n[...]\nToledo, the seat of the Castilian monarchy, was Rabbi Todros Abulafia (not to be confused with the Hebrew\n[...]\nof the same\n[...]\nand time),\n[...]\nRab, a chief rabbi of sorts to the Castilian Jewish community. Todros Abulafia was revered as a senior teacher-figure by the kabbalists of one of the early circles of those who were composing that which later came to be known as Sefer ha-Zohar (The Book of Radiance).\n[...]\nSome recent scholars have suggested that because the Zohar stretches beyond the work not only of any one person but also any one circle of mystic fellowship, it is more accurate to refer to this monumental corpus as a literature unto itself that developed in stages over the span of sixty years, from 1270 to 1330. The Zohar first emerged in this time and place in sections and short manuscript pamphlets circulated by one rabbi, Rabbi Moshe de Leon. De Leon wrote numerous kabbalistic books under his own name, but he claimed to have discovered a hitherto unknown ancient mystical manuscript, written in a mysterious-sounding Aramaic by the revered second-century tannaitic sage, Rabbi Shimon bar YoбёҘai. This fact is key in understanding both the literary genre itself and the powerful, nearly instant, appeal of the text, for the Zohar is the example par excellence of medieval pseudepigraphyвҖ”a phenomenon mentioned in Episode 3 in which a later (in this case medieval) author successfully attributes a work to a revered sage of a bygone, classical age. The Zohar was successfully attributed, with some scattered skepticism, in traditional circles to Rabbi Shimon bar YoбёҘai until the rise of modern critical study of the text began to develop and unfold, culminating in the academic research of the pioneering scholar Gershom Scholem in the early and mid 20th century.\n[...]\nLetвҖҷs return to the fact that the Zohar was written in Aramaic, while virtually all the rest of kabbalistic texts from this period (along with those we discussed in Episode 3) were composed in Hebrew. An elegant and literary Hebrew was the language of religious writing in 13th Century Castile, so the ZoharвҖҷs distinctive language is notable.\n[...]\n- It is these mysteries and symbolic theological expositions that are the subject of this dialogue along the road, and thus the large majority of the main body of the Zohar is taken up with what may be characterized as mystical midrashimвҖ”units of discourse that seek to resemble some of the forms and methods of ancient Midrash, but\n[...]\nultimately concerned with the kabbalistic content of the ten sefirot, their\n[...]\nEin-Sof (Infinity), the interplay of Divine\n\n---\n\nTitle: Zohar\nURL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zohar\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nThe Zohar (Hebrew: Ч–Ц№Ч”Ц·ЧЁвҖҺ, romanized: ZЕҚhar, lit. 'Splendor' or 'Radiance') is a foundational work of Kabbalistic literature. It is a group of books including commentary on the mystical aspects of the Torah and scriptural interpretations as well as material on mysticism, mythical cosmogony, and mystical psychology. The Zohar contains discussions of the nature of God, the origin and structure of the universe, the nature of souls, redemption, the relationship of ego to darkness and \"true self\" to \"the light of God\".\n[...]\nThe Zohar was first publicized by Moses de LeГіn(c. 1240 вҖ“ 1305 CE), who claimed it was a Tannaitic work recording the teachings of Shimon ben Yochai(c. 100 CE). This claim is universally rejected by modern scholars, most of whom believe de LeГіn, also an infamous forger of Geonic material, wrote the book himself between 1280 and 1286. Some scholars argue that the Zohar is the work of multiple medieval authors and/or contains a small amount of genuinely antique novel material. Later additions to the Zohar, including Tiqqune hazZohar and Ra'ya Meheimna, were composed by a 14th century imitator.\n[...]\nThe original text of the Zohar\n[...]\nearly Kabbal\n[...]\ne.g. Isaac b. Samuel of Acre, David b. Judah the Pious, Israel Alnaqua, Alfonso de Zamora\n[...]\nwas partly in Hebrew and partly in Aramaic. By the time of the first edition (1558) the text was entirely in Aramaic, with the exception of the Midrash haNe'elam, where Hebrew words and phrases are often employed as in the Babylonian Talmud\n[...]\nthe Midrash haNe'elam\n[...]\nmidrashim,\n[...]\nmedieval Hebrew, and its midrash\n[...]\nAccording to Scholem, the Zohar can be divided into 21 types of content, of which the first 18 (a.вҖ“s.) are the work of the original author (probably de Leon) and the final 3 (t.вҖ“v.) are the work of a later imitator.\n[...]\nb. Book of Concealment\n[...]\nЧЎЧӨЧЁЧҗ\n[...]\nЧҰЧ ЧҷЧўЧ•ЧӘЧҗ\n[...]\nGreater Assembly (ЧҗЧ“ЧЁЧҗ ЧЁЧ‘Чҗ)\n[...]\nThis part contains an explanation of the oracular hints in the previous section. Ben Yochai's friends gather together to discuss secrets of Kabbalah. After the opening of the discussion by ben Yochai, the sages rise, one after the other, and lecture on the secret of Divinity, while ben Yochai adds to and responds to their words. The sages become steadily more ecstatic until three of them die. Scholem calls this part \"architecturally perfect.\"\n[...]\nLesser Assembly (ЧҗЧ“ЧЁЧҗ Ч–Ч•ЧҳЧҗ)\n[...]\nAssembly of the Tabernacle (ЧҗЧ“ЧЁЧҗ Ч“ЧһЧ©ЧӣЧ Чҗ)\n[...]\nl. Secrets of Torah (ЧЎЧӘЧЁЧҷ ЧӘЧ•ЧЁЧ”)\n[...]\norical and mystical interpretations of Torah passages.\n[...]\nn. Zohar to the Song of Songs\n[...]\nr. Mystical Midrash (ЧһЧ“ЧЁЧ© Ч”Ч ЧўЧңЧқ)"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"79e3223a-ba20-4f6e-b874-a03376aa41